50|$|It was Shahīd ath-Thānī {{who took}} the concept of Nā'ib al-'Amm to its logical {{conclusion}} in the religious sphere and applied it {{to all of the}} religious functions and prerogatives of the Hidden Imām. Thus the judicial authority of the ulamā' now became a direct reflection of the authority of the Imām himself. It was now obligatory to pay the <b>religious</b> <b>taxes</b> directly to the ulamā' as the trustees of the Imām for distribution and the donor who distributed these himself was considered to obtain no reward. This is in direct contradiction to limits set by prior transgressions.|$|R
